    {
      "id": "6d46535cc939ded259520dbecbef8f0a90ccd858",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-04-22 18:25:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\n(2 comments)\n\nPatch is mostly good, but I think it makes sense to acutally use LOV_MAGIC_POSTFIX.\n\nThe other question I have about this part of LFSCK checking is during checking OST objects during orphan object scanning.  If the MDT finds an orphan OST object that references an MDT object with an unknown LOV EA (as opposed to an invalid LOV EA that doesn't have LOV_MAGIC_MAGIC), does it consider this object as \"used\" or does it consider it an orphan?  I think the correct/safe behaviour if an OST object parent FID references an MDT object with an unknown magic that it should be left as-is (assume valid).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f5ec66eb2270650ee20274df1f23813d4da8c770",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-04-22 20:17:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/e0cc0ea8-ca5a-11e3-9211-52540035b04c).  Ran 6 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b559b9e139f327524050daa435e8e5ea75be9e59",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-04-22 23:55:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/83527408-ca76-11e3-826c-52540035b04c).  Ran 13 tests.  2 tests failed: sanity-quota, replay-single.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "cc829217097972b354da733e805434de9c665007",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-04-23 00:08:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified-1\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/bf4e6060-ca77-11e3-9211-52540035b04c).  Ran 8 tests.  3 tests failed: conf-sanity, sanityn, sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a27a48398e998281e607e815929e6ab7b8ff7e1d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-04-23 00:25:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nDuring the orphan OST-object handling phase. If the OST-object reference back a MDT-object which contains an unknown LOV magic, then there are two cases:\n\n1) The magic contain the LOV_MAGIC_POSTFIX, then it is quite possible that it is a new magic downgrade from new Lustre release. Then the LFSCK will keep the MDT-object there without repairing. Otherwise,\n\n2) The magic should be a crashed one. Then the LFSCK will replace the crashed LOV EA with the orphan information.\n\nI think that we get agreement on the case 1. Then how about the case 2?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3068cf3312b0823f2ddb0c857ae4f4594283b327",
      "author": {
